# AVA — AI Assistant Context

This is the first file to load into any AI coding assistant (Claude, Codex, Cursor,
Windsurf, Copilot, Gemini, …) when working on the Asterisk AI Voice Agent. It gives your
assistant the project map, architecture vocabulary, engineering guardrails, and
contribution workflow so it can plan and review work the way maintainers do.

It is self-contained: everything an external contributor's assistant needs is either in
this file or in the committed docs it links to. If this file ever contradicts the code or
the docs, trust the code, then the docs — and please open an issue so we can fix it here.

> Last verified against: **v7.3.2** (2026-07). Freshness is
> checked as part of the release checklist (`docs/RELEASE_CHECKLIST.md`).

## What This Project Is

A self-hosted AI voice agent platform for Asterisk/FreePBX. Callers talk to an AI agent
over a real phone call; the engine bridges Asterisk audio to cloud or local AI providers,
handles barge-in, tool calling (transfers, email, calendar, HTTP lookups, MCP), and
records call history. Operators manage everything through a web Admin UI.

## Project Map (Core Components)

This is a monorepo with several production components. Always identify which component(s)
are in scope before planning work:

- **AI Engine (Python)**: `src/` — call orchestration, ARI integration, transport
  orchestration, providers/pipelines, tool calling, call history, metrics/health.
- **Local AI Server (Python)**: `local_ai_server/` — local STT/TTS/LLM backends
  (Vosk, Sherpa, Piper, Kokoro, llama.cpp, …) for local/hybrid deployments.
- **Admin UI**:
  - Frontend: `admin_ui/frontend/` (Vite/React/TypeScript, Vitest tests)
  - Backend: `admin_ui/backend/` (FastAPI) — config writes, agents store, container ops,
    setup wizard, system updates.
- **Agent CLI (Go)**: `cli/` — canonical commands are `agent setup`, `agent check`,
  `agent rca`, `agent update`, and `agent version`; older command names remain hidden
  compatibility aliases where supported.
- **Updater**: `updater/` — container image behind the Admin UI's Updates page.
- **Config & Baselines**: `config/` (live YAML + golden baseline configs) and
  `docs/baselines/golden/` (validated reference behavior per release).
- **Ops & Monitoring**: `docker-compose*.yml`, `monitoring/`, `scripts/`, `Makefile`.

Runtime data lives in `./data/` on the host (`/app/data/` inside containers): call history
SQLite (`call_history.db`) and the agents store (`agents.db`).

## Architecture Vocabulary (Must-Know Concepts)

Use these terms consistently and tie every change back to them:

- **Two-container core**: `ai_engine` (Python engine) + `admin_ui`; plus optional
  `local_ai_server` (local/hybrid pipelines) and `updater`.
- **Upstream audio transports**: AudioSocket (TCP) and ExternalMedia RTP (UDP). Never
  assume a default — check `config/ai-agent.yaml` and the active golden baseline. See
  `docs/Transport-Mode-Compatibility.md`.
- **Audio profiles & negotiation**: codec/sample-rate decisions belong in
  `TransportOrchestrator` (`src/core/transport_orchestrator.py`) and YAML `profiles` —
  never hard-coded in providers.
- **Agents (v7.0+)**: the primary way operators define who answers a call. Agents live in
  `agents.db` (managed via the Admin UI Agents page, CRUD in
  `admin_ui/backend/agents_store.py`), carry prompt, greeting, provider/pipeline
  selection, tools, audio profile, and per-agent email settings. At call time the engine
  resolves the agent via `src/core/agent_store.py` into a `ContextConfig`
  (`src/core/transport_orchestrator.py`). Legacy YAML `contexts` remain as the headless
  fallback (used when `agents.db` is absent or unreadable). See `docs/AGENTS.md`.
- **ContextConfig**: the single runtime contract between config sources (agents.db or
  YAML) and providers — prompt, greeting, provider/pipeline, tools, audio profile, email
  overrides. Extending per-agent behavior means extending ContextConfig and threading the
  field through `provider_context` in `src/engine.py` (the per-agent email fields are the
  reference example of this pattern).
- **Session state & call lifecycle**: `SessionStore` (`src/core/session_store.py`) is the
  authoritative state layer. Never introduce new ad-hoc dictionary call state.
- **Caller inactivity (v7.3.1+)**: `NoInputWatchdog` (`src/core/no_input_watchdog.py`)
  owns caller-silence check-ins and terminal timeout. Inbound calls inherit the enabled
  30-second default; outbound calls require a per-agent opt-in. Its speech must use the
  active provider/pipeline voice, and terminal hangup must go through the engine's shared
  caller-audio drain path so both AudioSocket and ExternalMedia/RTP finish playback first.
  Do not add provider-owned competing silence hangups.
- **Playback & gating**: `PlaybackManager` / `StreamingPlaybackManager` produce downstream
  audio; `ConversationCoordinator` and `AudioGatingManager` control capture, gating, and
  barge-in.
- **Provider modes**:
  - **Full-agent (monolithic) providers** — provider handles STT+LLM+TTS end-to-end over
    one session (`src/providers/`): OpenAI Realtime, Deepgram Voice Agent, Google Live
    (incl. Vertex AI Live), ElevenLabs Agent, xAI Grok, Local full-agent. Multiple
    instances of the same provider type are supported.
  - **Modular pipelines** — separate STT/LLM/TTS adapters resolved by
    `PipelineOrchestrator` (`src/pipelines/orchestrator.py`): OpenAI, Deepgram (+ Flux),
    Google, Azure, ElevenLabs, Groq, Ollama, Telnyx (LLM), MiniMax (LLM), CambAI, Local.
- **Voice selection (v7.3.0+)**: voice belongs to agents. Precedence: per-call override >
  agent voice (agents.db / YAML context `voice:` key) > provider default. Resolution lives
  in `resolve_effective_voice()`/`apply_context_voice()` (`src/core/transport_orchestrator.py`);
  per-provider catalogs and metadata in `src/utils/voice_catalog.py` (single source shared
  by the engine's soft validation and `GET /api/config/providers/meta`). OpenAI Realtime,
  Google Live, and Deepgram validate against their closed catalogs and fall back on
  unknowns (never failing a call); Grok passes through (custom clone IDs); ElevenLabs
  Agent and the Local full agent never consume a context voice; pipeline TTS
  voices are per-pipeline (per-agent pipeline voice is future work). The resolved
  (voice, source) is logged per session and recorded in Call History.
  See `docs/VOICE_SELECTION.md`.
- **Tool calling**: tools register in `src/tools/registry.py` (categories: `telephony/`,
  `business/`, `http/`, MCP via `mcp_tool.py`) and are adapted per provider in
  `src/tools/adapters/` (OpenAI, Deepgram, Google, Grok, ElevenLabs). Schema formats vary
  per provider — see `docs/contributing/schema-reference.md` and
  `docs/contributing/COMMON_PITFALLS.md`. Tools run in three phases: pre-call, in-call,
  post-call, all dispatched by the engine.
- **Per-call overrides**: channel variables `AI_AGENT` (preferred — routes by agent slug,
  slug-first lookup), `AI_PROVIDER`, and `AI_AUDIO_PROFILE` override defaults per call.
  `AI_CONTEXT` is the legacy equivalent of `AI_AGENT` (display-name lookup) and keeps
  working, but new dialplans should use `AI_AGENT`
  (see `docs/Configuration-Reference.md`).
- **Live status & call history**: push-based live-status hub feeds the Admin UI dashboard;
  call history persists to SQLite (`src/core/call_history.py`).

## Engineering Guardrails (Non-Negotiable)

These are enforced in review and/or CI. Your assistant must apply them to every change:

1. **Never block the asyncio event loop.** No synchronous network/file I/O in the call
   path. Latency budgets: sub-2s perceived response for pipeline providers, sub-1s for
   full-agent providers.
2. **Use SessionStore for call state.** No new ad-hoc dicts keyed by call ID in
   `src/engine.py` or elsewhere.
3. **Golden baselines are protected.** `docs/baselines/golden/` +
   `config/ai-agent.golden-*.yaml` define known-good provider behavior. Don't break them;
   validate against them when touching providers or transports.
4. **Tests are required.** PRs need pytest (engine / `admin_ui/backend`) or Vitest
   (frontend) coverage for the change. CI enforces a coverage floor
   (see `--cov-fail-under` in `.github/workflows/ci.yml`) — never lower it.
5. **Every code change adds a `CHANGELOG.md` entry** under `[Unreleased]`
   (Keep a Changelog format), in the same PR.
6. **UI sync rule.** A new provider or any `ai-agent.yaml` schema change must update the
   provider form (`admin_ui/frontend/src/pages/ProvidersPage.tsx`) and the setup wizard
   (`admin_ui/backend/api/wizard.py`) in the same change.
7. **Form fields use the HelpTooltip pattern**
   (`admin_ui/frontend/src/components/ui/HelpTooltip.tsx`).
8. **Transport/codec logic lives in TransportOrchestrator + YAML profiles**, never inside
   provider adapters.
9. **Surgical diffs.** Every changed line traces to the task. Match existing style; don't
   reformat or "improve" adjacent code. Small, reviewable PRs.
10. **Never commit secrets or caller PII.** No API keys, private hostnames, phone numbers,
    emails, raw transcripts, tool arguments, or local configs. A call ID may appear only
    in revision-pinned release/RCA evidence when needed for traceability and must never be
    paired with caller identity. CI runs a secrets check; review `git diff` before pushing.
11. **Read `docs/contributing/` before implementing** — especially
    `architecture-deep-dive.md`, `code-style.md`, `COMMON_PITFALLS.md`, and the
    provider/tool/pipeline development guides when working in those areas.

## Contribution Workflow

- **Where tasks come from**: GitHub Issues (look for `good first issue`), GitHub
  Discussions, and `docs/ROADMAP.md`. Feature proposals follow `GOVERNANCE.md`
  (Discussion → spec → roadmap). Community chat: [Discord](https://discord.gg/ysg8fphxUe).
- **Branching**: fork the repo, create **one branch per PR** off the latest `main`, open
  the PR against `main`. Never stack multiple PRs on the same branch — each PR must
  contain only its own commits. Rebase on `main` before opening if your branch is old.
- **What CI gates** (`.github/workflows/ci.yml` and friends): Python compile + secrets
  check, pytest with coverage floor, Admin UI backend tests, frontend tests/build in the
  main CI workflow, Docker image size budgets, CodeQL and Trivy scans.
- **PR expectations** (see `.github/pull_request_template.md`): summary, linked issue,
  tests added/updated, CHANGELOG entry, docs updated, and — for anything touching the
  call path — evidence from at least one real test call (provider, transport, call ID or
  log excerpt, observed behavior).
- **Review**: single-maintainer review (`.github/CODEOWNERS`); automated review runs on
  PRs. Expect requests for tests and doc updates — they are part of "done".
- **Scoped contributions are welcome.** You can work on one provider, one tool, or one UI
  page without understanding the whole system — use the per-area guides in
  `docs/contributing/` and its `references/` implementation deep-dives.

